# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1903-st-louis-browns-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The **1901 Milwaukee Brewers** were an American professional baseball team.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] This was the final season of the Milwaukee Brewers team that operated from 1894 to 1901, one of multiple teams in Milwaukee's professional baseball history to use the Brewers nickname, and the only season the team competed at the major-league level.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Brewers finished eighth in the inaugural season of the American League with a record of 48 wins and 89 losses, 35+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] After the season, the major-league franchise relocated and became the St.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] Louis Browns, where they remained through the 1953 season, after which the franchise again relocated and became the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] A franchise in the minor-league American Association played in Milwaukee from 1902 through 1952 using the Milwaukee Brewers name.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] 4/25/01: In the first game of the season in Detroit, the Brewers held a 13–4 lead going into the ninth inning.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Detroit Tigers scored 10 runs in the bottom of the inning to win, a record which still stands as the greatest ninth inning comeback in major league baseball history.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the first for the franchise in St.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 78 wins and 58 losses.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The Milwaukee Brewers of the American League decided to relocate to St.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Ownership chose the name "Browns" on purpose, as the St.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns had won American Association titles from 1885 to 1889.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] That team moved to the National League in 1892, became the Perfectos in 1899, and has been known as the Cardinals since 1900.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The new Browns quickly tried to align itself with fans by raiding the rival Cardinals.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] A couple of Cardinals players were signed, including slick fielding future Hall of Fame shortstop Bobby Wallace and 1901 National League batting champion outfielder Jesse Burkett.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] While playing as the 1901 Brewers, the team had a record of 48–89 (.350) and finished in eighth place, while the 1902 Browns played to a record of 78–58 (.574) and finished in second place.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1903 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 33rd season of the franchise.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished sixth in the National League with a record of 58–80, 32 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1903 Brooklyn Superbas season** was a season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-brooklyn-superbas-season] The Superbas began their slide from contention in the National League by finishing in fifth place.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] The **1903 Chicago Cubs season** was the 32nd season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 28th in the National League, and the 11th at West Side Park.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished third in the National League with a record of 82–56.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] On September 18, 1903, the Phillies' Chick Fraser pitched a no-hitter in the second game of a double header against the Cubs at West Side Park.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-chicago-cubs-season] Fraser walked five batters, the Phillies committed four errors and won 10 to 0.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1903-st-louis-browns-season/1903-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished sixth in the American League with a record of 65 wins and 74 losses, 26½ games behind the Boston Americans.
